View(flights)
Dplyr & Tibble components:
  • ‘int’= “integers”
  • ‘dbl’ = “doubles” (real numbers)
  • ‘chr’ = “character vectors” (strings)
  • ‘dttm’ = “date-times” (a date + a time)
  • ‘lgl’ = “logical” (vectors that are only TRUE or FALSE)
  • ‘fctr’ = “factors” (represent categorical variables w/ fixed values)
  • ‘date’ = “dates”
Dplyr basics include the following:
  • (filter()) picks observations by value
  • (arrange()) reorders rows
  • (select()) picks variables by name
  • (mutate()) creates new variables w/ functions from existing variables
  • (summarise()) collapses many values down to a single summary

To determine if a value is missing use is.na(): An example: let x be Mary’s age. We don’t know how old she is.

x <- NA
is.na(x)
## [1] TRUE

Note: filter() only includes rows when condition = TRUE; it exclude FALSE & NA values. Want to preserve missing values? Ask for them like this:

df <- tibble(x = c(1, NA, 3))
filter(df, x > 1)
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##       x
##   <dbl>
## 1     3
filter(df, is.na(x) | x > 1)
## # A tibble: 2 x 1
##       x
##   <dbl>
## 1    NA
## 2     3

Examples of other helper functions you can use within the select() function:

  • starts_with(“abc”): matches names beginning with “abc”
  • ends_with(“xyz”): matches names ending with “xyz”
  • contains(“ijk”): matches names containing “ijk”
  • matches(“(.)\1”): selects variables matching a regular expression; specifically variables containing repeated characters.
  • num_range(“x”, 1:3): matches x1, x2 and x3.
  • use rename(): renames variables Example of rename() function

Note: mutate() adds new columns at the end of your dataset. To see all the columns use View(). Example of creating a narrower data set and changes with mutate.

flights_sml <- select(flights, 
                      year:day, 
                      ends_with("delay"), 
                      distance, 
                      air_time
)
mutate(flights_sml,
       gain = dep_delay - arr_delay,
       speed = distance / air_time * 60
)

summarise() collapses a data frame to a single row:

summarise(flights, delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   delay
##   <dbl>
## 1  12.6

summarise() works best with group_by() to go from analyzing the complete dataset to individual groups (e.g., a data frame grouped by date gives you average delay per date)

by_day <- group_by(flights, year, month, day)
summarise(by_day, delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 365 x 4

Example of exploring the relationship between the distance and average flight delay for each location:

by_dest <- group_by(flights, dest)
delay <- summarise(by_dest,
                   count = n(),
                   dist = mean(distance, na.rm = TRUE),
                   delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
)
delay <- filter(delay, count > 20, dest != "HNL")
ggplot(data = delay, mapping = aes(x = dist, y = delay)) +
  geom_point(aes(size = count), alpha = 1/3) +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

Guided example from this chapter about how to prepare this data for additional analyses:

  • Group flights by destination
  • Summarise to compute distance, average delay, and number of flights
  • Filter to remove noisy points and Honolulu airport (which is an outlier ) To deal with the tediousness of having to name each intermediate data frame use the pipe, %>%:
delays <- flights %>% 
  group_by(dest) %>% 
  summarise(
    count = n(),
    dist = mean(distance, na.rm = TRUE),
    delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>% 
  filter(count > 20, dest != "HNL")

%>% when reading code is pronounced “then” Examples: x %>% f(y) makes f(x, y) x %>% f(y) %>% g(z) makes g(f(x, y), z)

How to remove cancelled flights:

not_cancelled <- flights %>% 
  filter(!is.na(dep_delay), !is.na(arr_delay))
not_cancelled %>% 
  group_by(year, month, day) %>% 
  summarise(mean = mean(dep_delay))

The authors reccommend when doing an aggregation like above, it’s helpful include either a count (n()), or a count of non-missing values (sum(!is.na(x)))

delays <- not_cancelled %>% 
  group_by(tailnum) %>% 
  summarise(
    delay = mean(arr_delay)
  )
ggplot(data = delays, mapping = aes(x = delay)) + 
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 10)

How to create a scatterplot of number of flights vs. average delay:

delays <- not_cancelled %>% 
  group_by(tailnum) %>% 
  summarise(
    delay = mean(arr_delay, na.rm = TRUE),
    n = n()
  )
ggplot(data = delays, mapping = aes(x = n, y = delay)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 1/10)

Here’s how to filter out the groups with the smallest numbers of observations, and integrate ggplot2 into dplyr flows:

delays %>% 
  filter(n > 25) %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = n, y = delay)) + 
  geom_point(alpha = 1/10)

Useful ‘hot keys’ reccommended by the authors

  • Cmd/Ctrl + Enter: sends the whole block of code
  • Cmd/Ctrl + Shift + P : resends previously sent chunk from editor to console enabling editing of that intial block
